# React Component Rules

## Component Structure

- One component per file (with small helper components allowed)
- Use functional components with hooks (no class components)
- Keep components focused and small (<150 lines)

## Naming

- Component files: `PascalCase.tsx` (e.g., `GameBoard.tsx`)
- Component names must match file names
- Props interface: `ComponentNameProps` (e.g., `GameBoardProps`)

## Props

- Always define props interface explicitly
- Use destructuring in function parameters
- Provide default values when sensible

```tsx
interface ButtonProps {
  label: string;
  onClick: () => void;
  disabled?: boolean;
}

export const Button: React.FC<ButtonProps> = ({ 
  label, 
  onClick, 
  disabled = false 
}) => { ... }
```

## Hooks

- Custom hooks go in `src/hooks/` directory
- Hook names start with `use` (e.g., `useGameState`)
- Keep hooks focused on single concern
- Extract complex logic into custom hooks

## State Management

- Use Zustand store for global/shared state
- Use `useState` only for local UI state
- Avoid prop drilling - use store or context

## Performance

- Use `React.memo()` for expensive components
- Use `useCallback` for callbacks passed to children
- Use `useMemo` for expensive computations
- Don't over-optimize - only when needed
